At 4:30 in Iteania time, Colen didn't like getting up so early. The main reason was that he had to wake up the rest of his platoon. He silently got out of bed, put on his combat uniform, and slipped on his assault vest. From the storage cabinet, he gathered his equipment with care, picking up a particularly small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder, hung his helmet on a hook on his waistband. The helmet was equipped with a full set of gear, including a respirator, goggles, and other necessary items. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly stepped out of the barracks, his boots making a crunching sound as they landed on the mud and ice.
He took out a lighter from his jacket pocket and another cigarette from another pocket. After lighting the cigarette, he took a gentle puff, then opened the door. Over the past week, he had to strain every nerve to wake up his subordinates. He no longer used the preset alarm because half the time it didn't ring, and all that could be heard from the speakers was a faint hiss.
"Shall we wake them up?" Kuren turned around and saw Lieutenant Neminic approaching.
"Yes." Kuren answered.
"The method you're planning to use this time?"
Before Kuren could answer, the door opened and Harris, Kreis, and a few other people rushed out, already dressed and ready.
"Good morning," said Kress.
"What woke you up?" Kullen asked.
"First, we really don't want to see what method you intend to use to wake everyone up today," said a soldier named Ravik. "Second, the squad that wakes up first gets to enjoy breakfast before anyone else," he continued. "You know how terrible those breakfasts can be."
Kelon said, "You're right, Sergeant La维奇." He reached out and pressed the switch. Instantly, a piercing alarm sounded within the barracks. He heard someone shouting inside, accompanied by the sound of hurried footsteps.
"Good heavens, Varthuri," Nemiich said. "I thought they had already learned to get up with you by now."
"My brothers at the boot camp did it,"科尔恩指着哈里斯、克雷斯和拉维克说。“不过话说回来，他们的班长和副班长都知道要在士兵起床前起床。”
A few seconds later, the rest of the company's soldiers ran out. They were all dressed and ready. Some new recruits looked groggy, while others appeared extremely irritated.
"Good morning everyone," Kolen said cheerfully.
"Allow me to be frank, sir, why did you choose to wake us up in that manner?" asked a raid team member ( corporal ).
"Because those ordinary alarm clocks are just a bunch of trash. And Daybreak never sleeps in," Colen said.
"Take your personal belongings," Colonel continued. As a captain and deputy commander of the company, he had the responsibility to assist Captain Bolatin Shao, the company commander, in supervising and leading the company. "We will not be returning. Sergeants and lieutenants, give yourselves and your team members 15 minutes for the final check and to pack the rations needed for today."
The members of Exodus Company dispersed quickly. They were part of the Second Assault Brigade. Before the merger, they had been two separate companies: Cohort and Dagger. This was a elite company, and Colen felt complicated about his promotion to lieutenant for many reasons.
Kurume walked side by side with Admiral William D. Leahy, the first-ranking officer in the front row, along the brightly lit roads of the base. The lights on both sides of the road were powered by generators. Most of the lights were red, which helped them avoid detection by enemy bombers. To counter them, Daybreak had already begun using the "Martlet" tactic in both the air and on the ground.
"A new day, and a new mission for Hell Pioneers," Nimitch said with a dry laugh. "Where are they going to send us this time?"
"Somewhere at a front-line base outside Ianoslos," Kolon said, taking a drag on his cigarette. He blamed Crees for getting him hooked on cigarettes, but thinking about the past year and all the battles they had gone through, he let it go. So he said nothing.
"Truly unfortunate," Nimitz murmured. "The front lines are under strain. All the reports coming from here are about 'Supporting the War Effort, Aid to the Kurgan Front.' Why not extend some support to the Haulan Front as well?"
"Good talk, brother," Kolon said, flicking the cigarette butt into the mud. "We'll go with the first tank platoon; we won't have to walk. Lieutenant Xiao should be there."
"Captain Xiao offered us a ride?" Nimitz asked, sounding somewhat surprised.
"Yes. To be honest, he's not as bad as I imagined. What I mean is, although he's not great, he's not someone you'd really dislike."
Kelon raised his thumb and index finger, pressing against the microphone at his throat, while shifting the backpack onto his back. "Exodus, assemble at the West Yard with all units after completing your missions. We will depart at 05:00 with the first tank platoon."
Every few seconds, he would receive responses from his platoon leaders. When they first arrived, Harris, Crees, and LaVick were lower-ranking sergeants. Since undergoing basic training on Earth, the four of them had always been good friends. Colen felt as if she had known them for much longer than just under two years. Now, all of them were platoon leaders, but starting from a week ago, when the front platoon leader was retired due to injuries inflicted by Daybreak's snipers, Crees had taken over leadership of the second platoon.
As they approached the vehicle depot, Kollon and Nimitz's eyes fell upon about eight Chronos main battle tanks and four Stryker armored vehicles. The crew members were scurrying around, making sure their war machines were in perfect working order. Kollon quickly spotted Lieutenant Bradlin Shaw, who was talking with the commander of the armored platoon. As they approached, Shaw glanced at them and came over, his usual cold expression showing no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nimich… Lieutenant Valteri…" he said. Colonel Ren slowed his steps, and Senior Lieutenant Xiao looked at Colonel Ren's holster before lifting his head. "Should the company be ready by now?"
